  "sections": {
    "Background": {
      "text": "Grossly visible blood in the anterior chamber of the eye\nTypically caused by\nblunt trauma\nto the orbit\nCan result in permanent\nvision loss\nOutcome dependent on prevention of rebleeding and control of intraocular pressure\nIn non-traumatic hyphema, all patients of African decent should be screened for\nsickle cell disease\nwith hemoglobin electrophoresis",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": [
        {
          "text": "blunt trauma",
          "url": "https://wikem.org/wiki/Blunt_eye_trauma"
        },
        {
          "text": "vision loss",
          "url": "https://wikem.org/wiki/Vision_loss"
        },
        {
          "text": "sickle cell disease",
          "url": "https://wikem.org/wiki/Sickle_cell_disease"
        }
      ]
    },
    "Clinical_Features": {
      "text": "Vision loss\nEye pain\nHistory of trauma to eye\nDirect and consensual photophobia\nNausea/vomiting\nHyphema grading\nGrade I: ≤ 1/3 anterior chamber volume\nGrade II: 1/3-1/2 anterior chamber volume\nGrade III: > 1/2 anterior chamber volume\nGrade IV: total anterior chamber volume, \"eight ball hyphema\"\nElevated grading correlates to increase in intraocular pressure\n[1]\n13.5% have IOP increase in Grade I to II\n52% with IOP increase in Grade IV",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": [
        {
          "text": "Vision loss",
          "url": "https://wikem.org/wiki/Vision_loss"
        },
        {
          "text": "Eye pain",
          "url": "https://wikem.org/wiki/Eye_pain"
        },
        {
          "text": "Nausea/vomiting",
          "url": "https://wikem.org/wiki/Nausea/vomiting"
        }
      ]
    },
